A valid model

set.seed(794)
n <- 80
x <- runif(n)
beta_1 <- 3.5
sigma <- .6
y <- beta_1 * x + rnorm(n, sd = sigma)
df <- data.frame(x, y)
m1 <- lm(y ~ x, data = df)

A valid model

Residual plot

plot(m1, 1)

QQ plot

plot(m1, 2)

Scale Location plot

plot(m1, 3)

Residual plot

plot(m1, 4)

Plot Quartet

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(m1)

What can break?

  1. Unbiased estimation of \(\hat{\beta}\)
  2. Accurate assessment of \(SE(\hat{\beta})\)
    • p-values
    • CI's

Checking for breaks

it <- 5000
beta_hats <- rep(NA, it)
capture <- rep(FALSE, it)
for(i in 1:it) {
  y <- beta_1 * x + rnorm(n, sd = sigma)
  m <- lm(y ~ x)
  beta_hats[i] <- m$coef[2]
  ci <- confint(m)[2, ]
  capture[i] <- (ci[1] < beta_1 & beta_1 < ci[2])
}

Checking for breaks

hist(beta_hats)
abline(v = mean(beta_hats), col = "tomato")

Checking for breaks

Bias in \(\hat{\beta}\)?

mean(beta_hats) - beta_1
## [1] 0.000283525

Accurate assessment of \(SE(\hat{\beta})\)

mean(capture)
## [1] 0.9482

Let's break something

Non-constant variance

set.seed(794)
n <- 80
x <- runif(n)
y <- beta_1 * x + rnorm(n, sd = .93 * x)
df <- data.frame(x, y)
m1 <- lm(y ~ x, data = df)

Non-constant variance

Checking for breaks

it <- 5000
beta_hats <- rep(NA, it)
capture <- rep(FALSE, it)
for(i in 1:it) {
  y <- beta_1 * x + rnorm(n, sd = .93 * x)
  m <- lm(y ~ x)
  beta_hats[i] <- m$coef[2]
  ci <- confint(m)[2, ]
  capture[i] <- (ci[1] < beta_1 & beta_1 < ci[2])
}

Checking for breaks

hist(beta_hats)
abline(v = mean(beta_hats), col = "tomato")

Checking for breaks

Bias in \(\hat{\beta}\)?

mean(beta_hats) - beta_1
## [1] -0.004152782

Accurate assessment of \(SE(\hat{\beta})\)

mean(capture)
## [1] 0.9106

Activity

With a partner (there needs to be one computer between you), choose one of thefollowing components of the linear model to break, then assess what goes wrong.

  1. Linear trend in mean function
  2. Normality of errors
  3. (Independence of errors)
